Pseudochorthippus de novo reference

For this project we created baits based on a transcriptomic reference, which means that some bait would span two adjacent exons making them less efficient for capture, therefore we increased tiling to mitigate such a problem.
After a successful capture we got the data back and it was mapped to the original transcriptomic reference, which I think creates some issues, mainly mapping artifacts:

  • Reads would be heavily clipped because now they will contain introns and other exon-adjacent sequence present in the genomic DNA but not in the transcriptomic reference
  • If clipping is not perfect this can create fake SNPs at the (invisible) exon junctions in the reference transcriptome
    Due to this problems the objective now is to create a mapping reference based on the assemblies made from all the individuals captured and assembled within Captus.

This document explains the process of going down from all the contigs per sample, to a single locus representative that includes the non-coding sequence adjacent to the areas on which the baits were designed. This should fix the mapping issues and allow more reliable SNP calling.

1. Demultiplex assembled contigs

Vitali clustered all the assemblies from all the samples using Captus. I took the clustering input file called clustering_data/clustering_input_complete.fasta.gz and re-process it. The first step is to separate the contigs per sample:

mkdir clustering_data/demultiplexed
demuxbyname.sh \
in=clustering_data/clustering_input_complete.fasta.gz \
out=clustering_data/demultiplexed/%.fa \
delimiter=pipe

Which creates a .fa per sample inside folder clustering_data/demultiplexed

2. Reduce assembly redundancy sample-wise

The second step is to remove redundant contigs from each assembly. We consider redundant any contig similar to another in >= 95% identity over 50% its length. We cluster them using mmseqs2 and keep the cluster representatives.

cd clustering_data/demultiplexed
for file in *.fa; do
	mmseqs easy-cluster $file ${file//.fa/_cl95_cov50} tempDir \
	-s 7.5 -c 0.50 --cov-mode 1 \
	--min-seq-id 0.95 --cluster-mode 2 --cluster-reassign \
	--gap-open 3 --gap-extend 1 --kmer-per-seq-scale 0.8
	rm -rf tempDir 
	rm ${file//.fa/_cl95_cov50}_all_seqs.fasta
	rm ${file//.fa/_cl95_cov50}_cluster.tsv
	rm $file
	mv ${file//.fa/_cl95_cov50}_rep_seq.fasta $file
done

Now all the .fa files inside clustering_data/demultiplexed are only the cluster representatives, and most of the redundancy has been eliminated.

3. Marker extraction with Captus

For this step we used as assemblies the demultiplexed contigs (clustering_data/demultiplexed/*.fa), we import them to a assemblies directory called 02_assemblies. The really important part is to use the correct reference for extraction: the file baits/bait_regions_nrDNA_mtDNA_Wolbachia.fasta contains only the gene regions from were the baits were created as well as the nuclear ribosomal cistron and mitochondrion from Pseudochorthippus as well as the ribosomal genes from Wolbachia (never use as reference the baits themselves i.e. the 120bp segments used for the oligos at Rapid Genomics). Another important point is to only extract the best match to reference from each samples (exclude all potential paralogs) using --max_paralogs 1:

captus_assembly-runner.py extract \
-a 02_assemblies -f clustering_data/demultiplexed/*.fa \
-o 03_extractions_maxpar1 \
-d baits/bait_regions_nrDNA_mtDNA_Wolbachia.fasta \
--max_paralogs 1

The recovered length and identity to reference across all samples was excellent (just one sample somewhat failed FOR881):

Recovered length:

Identity to reference:


TIP: these heatmaps are dynamic and are produced after the extraction steps finishes in Captus, sometimes is useful to explore them to learn about the samples.

4. Concatenate all matched contigs across samples

Captus produces a file that contains the match inside the context of the contig(s) where it was found: DNA_matches_flanked.fna. We concantenate all these files across all samples:

cat 03_extractions_maxpar1/*__captus-ext/04_misc_DNA/DNA_matches_flanked.fna \
> denovo_reference/all_flanked_matches.fasta

The I wrote a python script best_match_per_locus.py to extract the best representative among all samples for each locus. The best representative has the longest contig length, highest similarity to reference, and highest percent recovered:

python best_match_per_locus.py \
denovo_reference/all_flanked_matches.fasta \
denovo_reference/best_flanked_matches.fasta

5. Clustering leftovers

We have used all the contigs that had hits to the reference, but a good proportion of the contigs remain unassigned. This is mainly because the capture process is not perfectly specific and other genomic regions get "carried over", sequence and assembled. We can cluster the leftover contigs, select cluster representatives that are present in most of the samples, and incorporate them as part of the reference. One could include the SNPs called over these additional contigs or simply exlude them, however including them in the mapping is important as a "read sponge" in case that there are ambiguous mappings, avoinding supurious, forced mappings to the reference loci on which we are more interested.
First, concatenate all leftover contigs:

cat 03_extractions_maxpar1/*__captus-ext/06_assembly_annotated/leftover_contigs.fasta.gz \
> leftovers/all_leftovers_maxpar1.fasta.gz

And then we perform clustering with mmseqs2:

mmseqs easy-cluster leftovers/all_leftovers_maxpar1.fasta.gz \
leftovers/all_leftovers_maxpar1_cl90_cov50 \
leftover/tmpDir \
-s 7.5 -c 0.50 --cov-mode 2 --min-seq-id 0.90 --cluster-mode 1 \
--single-step-clustering --cluster-reassign \
--gap-open 3 --gap-extend 1 --kmer-per-seq-scale 0.8

Finally, using another python script process_leftovers.py we extract only the cluster representatives that are longer than 200bp (4th argument) and that represent cluster that include 50 or more samples (3rd argument):

python process_leftovers.py \
leftovers/all_leftovers_maxpar1_cl90_cov50_all_seqs.fasta \
leftovers/all_leftovers_maxpar1_cl90_cov50_reps_minsamples50_minlen200.fasta \
50 \
200

6. Final reference file

The reference file I am sending is called best_flanked_matches_leftovers_maxparalogs1.fasta which is the result of concatenating best_flanked_matches.fasta and all_leftovers_maxpar1_cl90_cov50_reps_minsamples50_minlen200.fasta. I only replace the nuclear ribosomal cistron with a complete assembly (nrDNA) as well as the mitochondrial genome (mtDNA).
